Prediction 1: Berry Phase Separation

The Berry phase accumulated by the state \|0⟩ (standing wave) over one
ouroboros cycle differs from that of \|±1⟩ by **5.63 radians (≈
1.79π)**. This is nearly maximal separation on the circle. It arises
because \|0⟩ has u ⊥ v (forward and inverse spinors orthogonal), causing
the Bloch vector to trace a fundamentally different path on S² during
the cycle. The path for \|0⟩ encircles the origin of the complex overlap
plane; the paths for \|±1⟩ do not. This is a topological distinction
that cannot be removed by continuous deformation.

**Why this matters:** If the Berry phase separation matches, the
non-destructive readout mechanism works. The trit value is encoded in a
geometric phase, measurable by interferometry without collapsing the
state. This is the foundation of merkabit computation: read by
circumnavigating, not by collapsing.

**If it fails:** A separation significantly below 5.63 rad (e.g., \< 3
rad) would indicate the dual-spinor counter-rotation is not producing
the predicted geometric phase structure. The readout mechanism would not
work as designed.

Prediction 2: Quasi-Period 3.3T

When the cell is initialised in \|+1⟩ and driven stroboscopically, the
coherence C(nT) oscillates with a dominant frequency of approximately
0.30/T, corresponding to a quasi-period of **3.3 Floquet periods**. This
is not exactly 3 (not a Z₃ time crystal) but an irrational number
arising from the beat between two incommensurate Floquet quasi-energies
at ±0.610π and ±0.010π. The system is a *discrete time quasi-crystal*
(DTQC), the temporal analogue of a Penrose tiling.

**Why this matters:** The quasi-periodicity ratio encodes the ratio of
base winding (P gate, period-12 closure) to fiber winding (symmetric
rotations, \~π total), which is the geometric signature of the Hopf
fiber structure. If the quasi-period matches, the fiber topology is real
and physical.

**If it fails:** A dominant period of exactly 2 (standard Z₂ DTC) would
mean the pentachoric structure collapses to ordinary Ising physics. An
aperiodic signal with no dominant frequency would indicate
thermalisation.

Prediction 3: Exact Z₂ Symmetry

The coherence of \|−1⟩ at every stroboscopic time must be the exact
negative of the coherence of \|+1⟩: **C(\|−1⟩, nT) = −C(\|+1⟩, nT)** for
all n. In simulation, this holds to machine precision (\< 10⁻¹⁴). The Z₂
symmetry is the forward/inverse spinor exchange symmetry of the
dual-spinor architecture. It is exact, not approximate, because the
Floquet drive treats both spinor modes with identical coupling
strengths.

**Why this matters:** The Z₂ symmetry is what protects the Berry phase
separation (symmetry-protected topological order). It is also the
symmetry that makes the time-crystalline phase possible. If Z₂ holds
exactly, the merkabit's balanced ternary structure (+1, 0, −1) is
physically realised, with \|0⟩ as the unique symmetry-invariant state.

**If it fails:** Systematic deviation \> 5% would indicate the physical
implementation breaks the forward/inverse symmetry. This is testable
independently of the other predictions and is the easiest to verify.

Prediction 4: 91% Central Detection Rate

When a single-gate error is injected at the central qubit (qubit 0,
which has 6 neighbours), the pentachoric detection mechanism identifies
the error in **91% of cases** within τ = 5 ouroboros steps (the
chirality rotation period). Detection occurs when a neighbouring qubit's
absent gate matches the error gate during its chiral rotation.

**Protocol:** Inject a known error (remove one of the 4 active gates) at
the central node at a random time step. Continue the Floquet drive for 5
additional steps. Extract syndromes from all 6 neighbours. An error is
detected if any neighbour's syndrome indicates an inconsistency with the
central node's expected gate assignment.

**Why this matters:** This tests the core error correction mechanism:
pentachoric gate complementarity. The 91% rate is a geometric
consequence of having 6 neighbours each rotating through 5 gate
positions. It requires no ancilla qubits, no classical processing, and
no external correction circuit. If it matches, error correction is a
property of the geometry.

**Boundary comparison:** Ring qubits (3 neighbours each) should show
detection rates of approximately 85--88%, giving a boundary gap of
\~3--5%. This gap is predicted to close when fiber detection channels
are activated (Prediction 5 extension).

Prediction 5: DTC Robustness to 10% Gate Noise

Add Gaussian noise with standard deviation ε = 0.10 to every gate angle
in every Floquet period. After 50 periods, the oscillation amplitude of
C(nT) for \|+1⟩ should remain **above 0.3** (on a scale where the clean
amplitude is approximately 1.5). In simulation, the amplitude actually
*increases* slightly with moderate disorder, characteristic of many-body
localisation enhancing the time-crystalline phase.

**Why this matters:** This is the DTC survival test. A true time crystal
resists thermalisation; noise does not destroy the order. If the
merkabit's three-level geometric error correction IS the mechanism
preventing thermalisation (as the Floquet analysis indicates), then the
DTC should survive noise levels consistent with the error correction
threshold (\~22%). Survival at ε = 0.10 is well within this bound.

**If it fails:** If the oscillation decays to zero within 50 periods at
ε = 0.10, the system thermalises and is not a time crystal. This would
indicate the geometric error correction is insufficient for
thermalisation protection in a physical system.

7\. Interpretation

**Full success (5/5):** All five predictions confirmed within stated
tolerances. The pentachoric Floquet drive produces a discrete time
quasi-crystal with geometric error correction and topologically
protected readout. Merkabit architecture is physically realised. Next
step: scale to 19-node and 37-node cells, implement inter-cell coupling,
demonstrate logical operations.

**Partial success (3--4/5):** Core physics present but specific
quantitative predictions off. Most likely cause: the mapping from
idealised pentachoric gates to physical pulse sequences introduces
systematic errors. Recalibrate the gate angle table and re-run. The
architecture is sound; the implementation needs tuning.

**Partial failure (1--2/5):** The Z₂ symmetry test (P3) and the DTC
robustness test (P5) are the most robust predictions; if either fails,
the dual-spinor architecture is not realised in the physical system. If
only P1 (Berry phase) or P2 (quasi-period) fail, the issue is likely in
the specific gate angle values, not the architecture.

**Full failure (0/5):** The 7-qubit hexagonal cell driven by the
pentachoric sequence does not behave as a merkabit. Either the physical
system does not implement dual-spinor modes, or the mapping from
abstract gates to physical pulses is fundamentally wrong. The
architecture remains mathematically valid but does not describe this
physical system.

8\. Estimated Resources

**Circuit depth:** 36 single-qubit gates per Floquet period (3 gates ×
12 steps). For 50 periods: 1,800 single-qubit gates total. No two-qubit
gates required for the core protocol.

**Shots:** Standard quantum tomography requires \~1,000 shots per
measurement basis per qubit. With 3 Pauli bases and 7 qubits,
approximately 21,000 shots per time point. For 50 stroboscopic time
points: \~1,000,000 total shots. At typical superconducting processor
speeds (\~10µs cycle time + reset), this is \~10 seconds of quantum
processor time.

**Classical post-processing:** State tomography reconstruction, Fourier
analysis of C(nT), Berry phase extraction from Ramsey fringes. Standard
tools; no specialised software required.

**Total estimated wall time:** One day of quantum processor access
(including calibration, state preparation optimisation, and multiple
runs for statistics). Classical analysis: one additional day.

9\. Connection to Existing Experiments

This protocol is closely related to three recent experiments that
validate the feasibility of each component:

**Mi et al. (Nature, 2022) and Zhang et al. (Nature, 2024):**
Demonstrated discrete time crystals on Google Sycamore and IBM Eagle
processors. These used periodic Ising drives on chain and 2D lattice
geometries. The merkabit protocol replaces the Ising drive with the
pentachoric sequence on the same hardware topology.

**Frey and Rachel (Science Advances, 2022):** Demonstrated a Floquet
topological phase on a superconducting processor. Measured topological
invariants via stroboscopic state tomography. The same measurement
approach applies directly to Predictions 1--3.

**He et al. (Phys. Rev. X, 2025):** Demonstrated a discrete time
quasi-crystal (DTQC) using NV centres in diamond. Observed
quasi-periodic subharmonic response with irrational frequency ratio.
Prediction 2 tests the same phenomenon with a specific predicted ratio
determined by pentachoric geometry.

Appendix: Qiskit Circuit Skeleton

The following pseudocode gives the structure of one Floquet period in
Qiskit. The exact gate angles for each step k are given in the table in
Section 3.

\# One Floquet period on 7 qubits

for k in range(12): \# 12 ouroboros steps theta_P, theta_Rz, theta_Rx =
angles\[k\] for q in range(7): \# all 7 qubits \# P gate (asymmetric
phase) qc.rz(+theta_P/2, q) \# forward mode qc.rz(-theta_P/2, q) \#
inverse mode \# Symmetric rotations qc.rz(theta_Rz, q) qc.rx(theta_Rx,
q)

*Note: The P gate implementation depends on the physical encoding of the
dual-spinor modes. In a dual-rail encoding (two transmon modes per
merkabit), P is a differential phase shift between the rails. In a
single-transmon encoding where \|0⟩ and \|1⟩ represent the two spinor
components, P is equivalent to Rz with opposite sign convention. The
experimentalist should choose the encoding that best matches their
hardware and implement P accordingly.*

